    law_category: "labor",
    article_num: "179",
    text: "The employer may terminate the employment contract if there is a justified reason related to the employee's work capacity and conduct: 1) if they do not achieve work results or do not have the necessary knowledge and skills to perform the jobs they are working on; 2) if they have been convicted by a final judgment for a criminal offense at work or related to work; 3) if they do not return to work with the employer within 15 days from the expiry of the suspension of employment from Article 79 of this Law, or unpaid leave from Article 100 of this Law. The employer may terminate the employment contract of an employee who through their own fault commits a breach of work obligation: 1) if they perform work duties carelessly or negligently; 2) if they abuse their position or exceed their authority; 3) if they use work resources uneconomically and irresponsibly; 4) if they do not use or misuse provided personal protective equipment or gear; 5) if they commit another breach of work obligation established by a general act or employment contract. The employer may terminate the employment contract of an employee who does not respect work discipline: 1) if they unjustifiably refuse to perform tasks and execute the employer's orders in accordance with the law; 2) if they do not submit a certificate of temporary incapacity for work within the meaning of Article 103 of this Law; 3) if they abuse the right to absence due to temporary incapacity for work; 4) due to coming to work under the influence of alcohol or other intoxicants, or use of alcohol or other intoxicants during working hours, which has or may have an impact on work performance; 5) (ceased to be valid by decision of the Constitutional Court); 6) if they provided false information that was decisive for establishing the employment relationship; 7) if an employee working on jobs with increased risk, for which special health capacity is stipulated as a special condition for work, refuses to undergo a health capacity assessment; 8) if they do not respect work discipline prescribed by the employer's act, or if their behavior is such that they cannot continue working with the employer. An employee's employment may terminate if there is a justified reason related to the employer's needs: 1) if due to technological, economic or organizational changes the need for performing certain work ceases or the volume of work decreases; 2) if they refuse to conclude an annex to the contract within the meaning of Article 171 paragraph 1 items 1–5 of this Law.",
